Katana

Target IP: 192.168.167.83

Scanning



There are six TCP ports open on the target machine. Looks like there are four HTTP applications, one SSH, and one FTP!

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The source-code does not have any useful information either.


Running gobuster dir -u http://192.168.167.83 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt -x php,html,txt gave us the most important results above.


The /ebook is the most interesting directory as it is using CSE Bookstore 1.0 and this is vulnerable unauthenticated RCE. I was also able to login using default credentials admin:admin. Before trying to exploit this vulnerablity, I wish to enumerate further.

Port 8088: HTTP

The same webpage as port 80 application is displayed for this port too. The source-code does not have anything useful either.


Running a gobuster scan again against this port shows different directories compared to port 80.


Browsing to /docs page tells us the version and name of the application running on this port.


The /phpinfo.php page contains important information about the host such as the kernel version, PHP version, etc. The /protected page prompts us to login.


The /upload.html is an interesting page as it allows us to upload files to the target machine. Maybe we can perform file upload attack?

Port 8715: HTTP

This application asks us to login. But we do not know the username and password.

Exploitation

Port 80: HTTP

Running the Online Book Store 1.0 - Unauthenticated Remote Code Execution against port 80 /ebook did not work. It looks like the web server does not have write permissions.

Port 8088: HTTP


During enumeration, I found a file upload feature located at upload.html. Time to test this feature. I started by creating a file called test.txt with the content Hi!. I was able to upload this file successfully! There is an important message stating the file we uploaded gets moved to another web server (maybe another port on the target machine?). The uploaded file is also prefixed with katana_.


WTF! After using the default credentials admin:admin, I was able to successfully login as admin on port 8715 and view the uploaded content! I should be able to upload a reverse shell script and gain a reverse connection now from the target host!


I used PHP PentestMonkey reverse shell script. I uploaded it successfully.


To activate the script, I went to http://192.168.167.83:8715/katana_shell.php. And, I gained a connection back from the target host. Now I have a foothold on the machine as www-data.

Privilege Escalation


Running cat /etc/passwd shows us the password hash of root and katana users. I copied the two hashes and stored them in a file called hash. The hashes are in sha512crypt format, so this should be crackable using hashcat. Why do I have a feeling the password hash of root user is uncrackable?


I did some further enumeration while I was running john to crack the password hashes. Then I stumbled upon this! It looks like we can take advantage of this capability weakness of Python to gain a root shell.


And now we have a root shell without having to wait for the password hashes to be cracked!

Flags


The local.txt flag file once I gained a foothold on the machine by exploiting the upload file feature on port 8088.


The proof.txt flag once I used Python 2.7 to exploit the capabilities weakness.
